by freema at 2026-07-07T13:51:34Z

We hit this exact problem in production, and this PR is the right fix.

Setup: a self-hosted MCP server exposed over HTTPS behind a reverse proxy (Cloudflare), with OAuth 2.1 Bearer auth. The `DnsRebindingProtectionMiddleware` default allowlist (`localhost` / `127.0.0.1` / `[::1]`) rejects the public host, so every authenticated `POST /_mcp` returns `403 "Forbidden: Invalid Host header."`.

What made this hard to diagnose: the host check runs **after** authentication, so clients that connect without a token first (MCP Inspector, CLI probes) fail earlier with `401` and never reach it — only fully-authenticated web connectors (e.g. the Claude/ChatGPT server-side proxies, which send `Host: <public-domain>`) trip the 403. That makes it look like an auth/CORS problem rather than a host-allowlist one.

We had to work around it by overriding the `mcp.server.controller` service to rebuild the transport without the middleware. A first-class `http.dns_rebinding_protection.allowed_hosts` / `enabled` option (exactly what this PR adds, keeping the other secure defaults) is the proper solution. Would be great to get this reviewed and merged. Thanks @Amoifr!

